head and I apologize. \x{2018}I\x{2019}ve not been here before.\x{2019}\x{2018}I think I came here once before,\x{2019} he says. \x{2018}But that was with someone from the neighbourhood and so it must have been quite a time ago now. I think it was here. The war had started, I know that. But not the air raids. I\x{2019}m sure it was before the air raids\x{2026}\x{2019}I nod again but I don\x{2019}t know what to say \x{2013}\x{2018}I lose track of the time,\x{2019} he sighs. \x{2018}Because there\x{2019}s no end, is there? They tell us that it\x{2019}s over, that we\x{2019}re at peace, but it doesn\x{2019}t feel like peace, doesn\x{2019}t feel like it\x{2019}s ended to me. What about you?\x{2019}I shake my head. I say something like, \x{2018}You\x{2019}re right.\x{2019}\x{2018}I\x{2019}m sixty-nine years old,\x{2019} he tells me. \x{2018}What good am I to anyone any more? I might as well be dead and be done with it. But I remember when I could carry sixty or seventy pounds, no trouble\x{2026}\x{2019}\x{2018}But you look like you\x{2019}re doing all right to me,\x{2019} I say \x{2013}He thanks me and asks me where I am from \x{2013}\x{2018}Mitaka,\x{2019} I tell him. \x{2018}What about you?\x{2019}\x{2018}Kinshi-ch\x{14d} originally,\x{2019} he says. \x{2018}But not any more, of course. I tell you, I was lucky to get away with the clothes on my back. I\x{2019}m staying with my daughter-in-law in Hakozaki now. But you can\x{2019}t depend on anyone these days, can you? And now they say my son is dead, she\x{2019}ll be looking to remarry and then what will I do \x{2026}?\x{2019}I nod and I watch him untie the towel from around his face and wipe the sweat from his forehead and then from his neck \x{2013}Now the old man gets to his feet and he looks at me \x{2013}\x{2018}Forgive me,\x{2019} the old man says. \x{2018}But are you ill?\x{2019}I shake my head. I say, \x{2018}Why do you ask that?\x{2019}\x{2018}I\x{2019}m sorry,\x{2019} he says. \x{2018}You\x{2019}re just very pale.\x{2019}\x{2018}Don\x{2019}t worry,\x{2019} I tell him. \x{2018}I\x{2019}m fine\x{2026}\x{2019}I pick up his bundle for him \x{2013}I hoist it onto his back \x{2013}It is a heavy load \x{2026}\x{2018}Thank you,\x{2019} he says as he walks off. \x{2018}And good luck\x{2026}\x{2019}I raise my cigarette to wave and I watch him go \x{2013}\x{2018}Don\x{2019}t give up,\x{2019} he shouts back. \x{2018}Never!\x{2019}*I walk up the clean little steps into Kanuma police station where the two officers behind the front desk bow, salute and welcome me back.\x{2018}I have a message from Tokyo for a Detective Ishida,\x{2019} announces one of the two men behind the desk \x{2013}\x{2018}Thank you,\x{2019} I say as he hands me the piece of paper and I put it in my pocket and thank him again \x{2013}\x{2018}Is Chief Tachibana here yet?\x{2019}\x{2018}No,\x{2019} he says. \x{2018}Maybe he\x{2019}s gone to the inn\x{2026}\x{2019}\x{2018}It\x{2019}s okay,\x{2019} I tell him. \x{2018}I\x{2019}ll go for a walk\x{2026}\x{2019}\x{2018}Where will you go?\x{2019} he asks me.\x{2018}To the river,\x{2019} I say. \x{2018}The\x{2026}\x{2019}\x{2018}The Black River?\x{2019} he asks.\x{2018}The Black River,\x{2019} I nod.I walk out of the police station. I do not run. My pocket on fire. I walk down the clean little steps. I do not run. My pocket on fire. I walk across the road. I do not run. My pocket on fire. I turn down another road. I do not run. My pocket on fire. I see the Black River \x{2013}And now I run. My pocket on fire. Now I run. My pocket on fire. Now I run. My pocket on fire. Down the banking \x{2013}My pocket on fire. And then I stop \x{2013}I take out the piece of paper:\x{2018}Leave Minami in Tochigi. Return to HQ. Inspector Adachi.\x{2019}Then, suddenly, a shout, \x{2018}There you are, Inspector Minami!\x{2019}\x{2018}I look up. Tachibana and Ishida coming down the banking \x{2013}Ishida; I no longer know who this Detective Ishida is \x{2026}\x{2018}Thought you\x{2019}d run back to Tokyo,\x{2019} shouts Tachibana \x{2013}\x{2018}I am sorry,\x{2019} I say. \x{2018}I just needed to go for a walk\x{2026}\x{2019}\x{2018}Don\x{2019}t apologize,\x{2019} says Tachibana. \x{2018}I bet you\x{2019}re not used to so much sake and good food these days, are you now, inspector?\x{2019}\x{2018}You were very generous,\x{2019} I tell him. \x{2018}Thank you.\x{2019}\x{2018}It\x{2019}s nothing,\x{2019} he says. \x{2018}We\x{2019}re all policemen\x{2026}\x{2019}I look at Ishida as I nod, \x{2018}All policemen\x{2026}\x{2019}\x{2018}Where to first, then?\x{2019} asks Tachibana, clapping his hands.*The same ancient small truck. The same old policeman in the driving seat. Tachibana gestures for me to sit up in the front while he and Ishida climb into the back again. The corrugated iron and the carpenter\x{2019}s tools gone today. The driver puts out his cigarette, straightens his cap and he starts up the truck as I hold on tight again \x{2013}I hate the countryside and I hate the people who live here \x{2013}This Land of the Grasping. This Land of the Greedy \x{2026}My eyes squinting in pain as the sunlight blinds me \x{2013}Everything black today. Everything black here \x{2026}The mountains black. The trees black \x{2013}No grey, no green and no purple \x{2026}No leaves and no flowers here \x{2013}There are no colours here \x{2026}Here, here, here, here \x{2013}In Kodaira country \x{2026}Here in \x{14c}aza-Hos\x{14d}, in Nikk\x{14d}-ch\x{14d}, where our small truck now pulls up outside the family home of Kodaira Yoshio, the ramshackle, broken-down family home where the uncle, the aunt and the cousin of Kodaira Yoshio still live, still working for Furukawa \x{2013}The uncle, the aunt and the cousin of Kodaira Yoshio who know why we are here, who know why we will keep knocking \x{2013}Until the cousin finally opens the door to invite us in, in through their rotting door and filthy genkan, through their stinking, fetid kitchen and into their dark and humid hearth and home \x{2013}Home. Home. Home. Home. Home. Home. Home \x{2026}The aunt scuttling off on her hands and her knees down another dark corridor. The uncle cross-legged in the hearth with a pipe. The uncle is an old man. The uncle does not speak \x{2013}\x{2018}He hates the police,\x{2019} says his son, the cousin. \x{2018}He thinks the police have got it in for him, got it in for our family\x{2026}\x{2019}\x{2018}Shut up, idiot!\x{2019} shouts the uncle as he picks up his pipe and gets to his feet. He walks off into the other half of the room, closing the screen doors behind him, still shouting, \x{2018}Idiot!\x{2019}\x{2018}What do you want?\x{2019} asks the cousin \x{2013}\x{2018}I want to know how often your cousin Yoshio comes back here,\x{2019} I tell him. \x{2018}I particularly want to know how often he came back here in the last two years, the dates he came and the things he might have brought back with him. It\x{2019}s important you remember\x{2026}\x{2019}\x{2018}Well, that\x{2019}s easy to remember,\x{2019} laughs the cousin now. \x{2018}Easy because we never saw him. He never came back here\x{2026}\x{2019}\x{2018}I don\x{2019}t believe you,\x{2019} I tell him. \x{2018}I don\x{2019}t believe you because I have already met six or seven other families near here who do remember that he came back, who do remember the dates and the things he brought back. So, I\x{2019}ll ask you again, to remember\x{2026}\x{2019}\x{2018}And I\x{2019}ll tell you again,\x{2019} says the cousin. \x{2018}He was never here. We heard he\x{2019}d been back to Tochigi, but we never saw him.\x{2019}\x{2018}You never saw him?\x{2019} I ask. \x{2018}He never came here?\x{2019}\x{2018}Why would he come here?\x{2019} asks the cousin. \x{2018}We\x{2019}ve nothing to sell him, nothing to buy from him. Why come?\x{2019}\x{2018}Because you\x{2019}re his family.\x{2019} I say. \x{2018}That\x{2019}s why.\x{2019}\x{2018}He never came back here,\x{2019} repeats the cousin \x{2013}In the dark, humid hearth and family home \x{2013}\x{2018}That\x{2019}s all I know, so that\x{2019}s all I\x{2019}ll say,\x{2019} the cousin says now. \x{2018}If you want to hear more, just knock on any door in the village.\x{2019}*His father was the eldest of the brothers, the neighbours tell us. He was a drinker, a gambler and a womanizer. He\x{2019}d had a farm, he\x{2019}d had an inn, the Hashimoto-Ya, the best in the village. But he lost them all through his gambling, his drinking and his womanizing. Even his horse. He ended his days at Furukawa Denki with the rest of them \x{2013}The father\x{2019}s first younger brother worked there all his life, the neighbours tell us. He was a slow worker but he was never absent. He worked only nights and he handed over all his pay to his mother. He was a stutterer and an idiot and he was the best of them \x{2013}The second younger brother is the uncle you met, the neighbours tell us. He was once the most dangerous man in the village; drank heavily and carried a knife. He has been in prison. He is still a short-tempered and aggressive man, but now he rarely speaks.The eldest brother of Kodaira Yoshio is not long dead, the neighbours tell us. He worked at Furukawa with the rest of them but he was fired because he stole from the other workers and he slept on the job. He went to Tokyo but soon came back, wandering from job to job, living off odd jobs and handouts. He was another one who rarely spoke. Even made his own wife and children eat their meals outside so he could eat in peace. In April last year he was arrested for stealing potatoes but he died before the case ever came to court \x{2013}His elder sister was much the same, the neighbours tell us. She worked at Furukawa Denki too, just like the rest of them. She married a man who was working there, but it didn\x{2019}t last more than a year. Then she married a Korean, again for less than a year. She was often hysterical and always a liar and died in January this year \x{2013}He was a bad lad himself, the neighbours are quick to tell us. But he wasn\x{2019}t the worst of the family. He was poor at his schoolwork, lazy and careless, but he never drank and he never gambled. He had the Kodaira family temper but he never fought with strangers \x{2013}It was a shock, then, when he killed his father-in-law \x{2013}He has a bastard son, the neighbours whisper to us. He must be about sixteen years old. Not a nice boy, a creep to the older kids and a bully to the younger ones. This was the son he had by the woman he had his affair with. This was the affair that made his first wife\x{2019}s family ask him to divorce her. That was the request that caused him to attack her family and murder her father \x{2013}That got him sent to prison \x{2013}That broke his mother\x{2019}s heart, the neighbours tell us now. For his mother was kind and honest, a loving and long-suffering woman \x{2013}\x{2018}But she lived her life in tears,\x{2019} they tell us. \x{2018}In tears\x{2026}\x{2019}*These mountains and valleys, these forests and fields, all look the same to me. Up the side of one small mountain and down the other side, a short tunnel here, a longer tunnel there, then up and down another slope and along another narrow road until the truck stops outside another small farm set back from the road by another small ditch at the foot of another small mountain. Now, again, Tachibana climbs out of the back of the truck and goes inside the house while Ishida, the driver and I sit and sweat inside the truck until Tachibana returns with another old farmer and introduces us to Mr. Samura \x{2013}\x{2018}The man who found the body,\x{2019} he says. \x{2018}Ishikawa\x{2019}s body.\x{2019}Then the driver starts the ancient truck again and slowly, very slowly we climb up the narrow road that leads up the small mountain slope behind the farm until Mr. Samura nods and grunts and Tachibana calls out to the driver who pulls up on the mountainside \x{2013}\x{2018}This is where he found her,\x{2019} says Tachibana. \x{2018}This place.\x{2019}\x{14c}aza Mizuki-chi, Manako-mura, Kami Tsuga-gun \x{2026}Everyone climbs out the truck. Everyone wipes their faces, wipes their necks and looks back down the mountain at the patchworks of fields and ditches, of farms and houses, and then everyone turns back round to stare up into another wood on another slope of another mountain, up into more shadows and more trees \x{2013}More black trunks, their branches and their leaves \x{2026}Samura points into the woods, \x{2018}It\x{2019}s that way\x{2026}\x{2019}He walks behind me. He walks behind me \x{2026}Now Tachibana and I follow the old farmer as he clambers up off the narrow road and into the woods, pointing this way and that as he goes, mumbling things we can\x{2019}t catch as the trees and their trunks stand closer and thicker together, Ishida following behind \x{2013}He walks behind me, through the trees \x{2026}Samura comes to a stop up ahead and looks round for us, shouting, \x{2018}This is the place. This is the place. This is the place\x{2026}\x{2019}The cicadas are deafening, the mosquitoes hungry again \x{2026}\x{2018}Last September,\x{2019} he says. \x{2018}I was looking for leaves\x{2026}\x{2019}Between the trees, the black trunks of the trees \x{2026}\x{2018}Leaves to dry out and to mix with tobacco\x{2026}\x{2019}Their branches and their leaves \x{2026}\x{2018}I trod right on her bones,\x{2019} he says \x{2013}Her white, naked body \x{2026}\x{2018}I\x{2019}d smelt her too,\x{2019} he says. \x{2018}As I was gathering up my leaves. But I\x{2019}d thought it was an animal, same as when I first trod upon her bones, then I slipped, I fell and I saw it wasn\x{2019}t no animal bones\x{2026}\x{2019}\x{2018}I look like bones \x{2026} I look like bones\x{2026}\x{2019}\x{2018}I knew they were human bones\x{2026}\x{2019}I turn round and around, among these trees and these branches, and I ask Samura, \x{2018}Are you sure this is the exact place?\x{2019}Samura 